              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Start with your core subject. Identify all major subtopics using keyword research tools, competitor gap analysis, and People Also Ask data. Group related keywords into clusters, assign each cluster a target page, and map the pillar-to-supporting-page relationship. Tools like Ahrefs, Semrush, or a well-structured spreadsheet work well for organising the output.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How is a topical map different from a content calendar?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A topical map is a strategic blueprint — what to cover and how it fits together. A content calendar is an operational schedule — when each piece gets written and published. The topical map comes first; the calendar is how you execute it.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How many pages should a topical map include?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
